S. Korea Financials | Asia Pacific

Korean bank stocks have pulled back since mid- July and have been rangebound as the reform story has lost momentum. On policy, we reiterate that there tends to be a tightening bias for regulatory backdrop when macro conditions are tough.

We need to wait for more clarity, but we believe this should be seen as mutual prosperity costs that we have already reflected in our 2025 model. We continue to prefer the relative laggards, such as HFG and SFG, considering their lower valuations and catching up to KFG on fundamentals.

On August 28, Lee Chan- jin, the newly appointed Governor of the Financial Supervisory Service (FSS), held a meeting with bank CEOs, with the key topics being: (1) Strengthening consumer protection and internal controls, and (2) expanding support for SMEs and SoHo. The FSS governor reiterated that financial protection will be its top priority going forward, and he also criticized the banks for seeking to sustain high net interest margins and grow interest income through retail collateralized loans.

On the retail lending side, the FSS reiterated its firm stance on controlling household lending. On loan pricing, there is a pending proposal to amend the Banking Act to exclude legal/peripheral costs (i.e., credit guarantee fees to be key factor) from lending spreads, with discussions expected at the September regular National Assembly session.

According to press reports (e.g., Moneytoday, Aug 27), the government is also considering raising the risk- Weightings for mortgage loans from 15% to 25%, but this would be limited to new originations and not the existing book so as to limit the impact on banks.

Regarding the raising of the education tax rate from 0.5% to 1%, which targets financial institutions with annual operating income exceeding W1tn, media reports (e.g., Hanyung, Aug 26) reported that the government is considering easing the tax burden due to strong opposition from the financial sector - around 60 institutions would face an additional W1.3tn costs annually (around W500bn for top 5 banks).

Base case scenario value, derived from a Gordon Growth model. We assume a risk- free rate of \(3.5\%\) , an equity risk premium of \(6.5\%\) and a beta of 1.05 to arrive at a cost of equity of \(10.3\%\) . Our sustainable ROE assumption is \(8.5\%\) - we believe the discount we had applied to our ROE assumption has been partially mitigated by the reform initiative. Our growth rate assumption is \(3.5\%\) . We derive a fair 2025e P/B multiple of \(0.74x\) .
- Stronger-than-expected earnings from non-bank portfolio- Lower-than-expected credit costs- More aggressive capital management
- Excessive competition in the credit card and SME segments, leading to earnings drag- Weaker macro conditions, leading to SME credit risk increase- Less-effective capital management

Base case scenario value, derived from a Gordon Growth model. We assume a risk- free rate of \(3.5\%\) , an equity risk premium of \(6.5\%\) and a beta of 1.05 to arrive at a cost of equity of \(10.3\%\) . Our sustainable ROE assumption is \(8.5\%\) and our growth rate assumption is \(3.5\%\) . We thus derive a fair 2025e P/B multiple of \(0.72x\) .
- Stronger-than-expected NIM recovery- Lower-than-expected credit costs- More proactive capital management
- Deterioration in the macro climate and competitive landscape- Potential drag on earnings from regulatory pressure- Weaker-than-expected capital structure

Base case scenario value, derived from a Gordon Growth model. We assume a risk- free rate of \(3.5\%\) , an equity risk premium of \(6.5\%\) and a beta of 1.03 to arrive at a cost of equity of \(10.2\%\) . Our sustainable ROE assumption is \(9.0\%\) , reflecting the improving total shareholder returns over the medium to long term. Our growth rate assumption is \(3.5\%\) . We thus derive a fair 2025e P/B multiple of \(0.79x\) on BVPS.
- Stronger-than-expected earnings from non-bank operations.- Lower-than-expected credit costs.
Quicker and higher capital outlay.
- Property market slowdown and slower-than-expected consumption.- Regulatory tightening.- Uncertainty on capital management.
